%N A287940 a(n) is the first odd prime greater than a(n-1) such that (a(1), ..., a(n)) forms a prime vector. a(1) = 3, a(2) = 5.
%C A287940 A prime vector of order n is an array of n distinct primes P = (p_1, p_2, ..., p_n) such that every sum of an odd number of consecutive elements is also prime. The weight of the prime vector is the sum of its elements. For full details see the Kamenetsky paper.
%C A287940 a(1)-a(24) were found by Herbert Kociemba.
%H A287940 Dmitry Kamenetsky, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1703.06778">Prime sums of primes</a>, arXiv:1703.06778 [math.HO], 2017.
%H A287940 Carlos Rivera, <a href="http://www.primepuzzles.net/puzzles/puzz_875.htm">Puzzle 875: Vector of primes that generates distinct primes</a>
%o A287940 (Python)
%o A287940 from itertools import islice
%o A287940 from gmpy2 import is_prime, next_prime
%o A287940 def agen(): # generator of terms
%o A287940     alst = [3]
%o A287940     while True:
%o A287940         yield int(alst[-1])
%o A287940         sums = [sum(alst[-i:]) for i in range(2, len(alst)+1, 2)]
%o A287940         p = next_prime(alst[-1])
%o A287940         while not all(is_prime(p+s) for s in sums):
%o A287940             p = next_prime(p)
%o A287940         alst.append(p)
%o A287940 print(list(islice(agen(), 18))) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Feb 01 2026
